                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/4015.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Brazilian Minister at Mexico City</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 2, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department is in receipt of a telegram from American Consul at Vera Cruz stating
                    that 1,500 Americans are still in Mexico City, many of whom are desirous of
                    leaving for Vera Cruz, but he understands the train which left Mexico City April
                    28 was the last opportunity for them to leave. Please investigate and urge upon
                    appropriate authorities the importance of providing facilities for these
                    Americans to leave Mexico City without delay. Kindly telegraph present
                    situation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
